Unsupervised - K means Clustering -WIne data

Mekala Soundaramuthu

8 December 2018

Problem Statement:

Cluster the given dataset into segments. The dataset has parameters indicating the metrics of wine samples.

Usually when dealing with an unsupervised learning problem, its difficult to get a good measure of how well the model performed. So we shall take a dataset for which we know the output and test the model performance.

Step 1: Import Data

Use read.csv to open both data sets and set them as df1 and df2.

Pay attention to what the separater (sep) is.

df1<-read.csv('C:\\Users\\Arun61\\Desktop\\DATA SCIENCE\\Megha Files\\25.11.18\\KMeans\\KMeans\\R\\winequality-red.csv',sep=";")
df2<-read.csv('C:\\Users\\Arun61\\Desktop\\DATA SCIENCE\\Megha Files\\25.11.18\\KMeans\\KMeans\\R\\winequality-white.csv',sep=';')

Now add a label column to both df1 and df2 indicating a label ‘red’ or ‘white’. - Output column mentioning the group name.

Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis

Create a Histogram of residual sugar from the wine data. Color by red and white wines.

library(ggplot2)

pl <- ggplot(wine,aes(x=residual.sugar)) + geom_histogram(aes(fill=label),color='black',bins=50)

pl + scale_fill_manual(values = c('#ae4554','#faf7ea')) + theme_bw()

pl + scale_fill_manual(values = c('red','white')) + theme_bw()

pl <- ggplot(wine,aes(x=volatile.acidity,y=residual.sugar)) + geom_point(aes(color=label),alpha=0.2)
pl

pl + scale_color_manual(values = c('#ae4554','#faf7ea')) +theme_dark()
